   "source": [
    "## 5. Bivariate Analysis"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9ac7d628",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Approach\n",
    "\n",
    "Two questions: **feature -> target** (which columns carry churn signal?) and **feature <-> feature** (redundancy). The association measure depends on the variable types:\n",
    "\n",
    "| Pair | Visual | Strength metric |\n",
    "|---|---|---|\n",
    "| numeric <-> numeric | heatmap | **Pearson r** (-1..+1) |\n",
    "| numeric <-> binary | histogram | **Point-biserial r** (-1..+1) |\n",
    "| categorical <-> categorical | bar / heatmap | **Cramer's V** (0..1) |\n",
    "\n",
    "> At ~594k rows significance tests are meaningless (p ~ 0 for everything), so we rank by **effect size** (|r|, Cramer's V) only.\n",
    "\n",
    "Part A = feature -> target; Part B = feature <-> feature."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "bd0a52cd",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Measure notes\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Pearson r** - compares two number columns. Score goes from -1 to +1: +1 means they rise together, -1 means one rises while the other falls, 0 means no connection. Only catches straight-line relationships and can be thrown off by extreme values.\n",
    "- **Point-biserial r** - same idea as Pearson r, but one column is a yes/no (0 or 1). It tells you how much the number differs between the \"yes\" group and the \"no\" group.\n",
    "- **Cramer's V** - used when both columns are categories (e.g. \"Contract type\" vs \"Churn\"). Score goes from 0 to 1: 0 = no connection, 1 = perfect connection. Adjusted so a bigger dataset doesn't fake a stronger score.\n",
    "\n",
    "How strong is the score? &lt;0.1 = basically nothing, 0.1–0.3 = weak, 0.3–0.5 = moderate, &gt;0.5 = strong."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a3abb4a3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 5.1 Setup"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "id": "7f6a14b7",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
