      "3 numeric + 16 categorical features ready.\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# =============================================================================\n",
    "# 5.1  Bivariate analysis - shared setup (depends only on `df` from Section 1)\n",
    "# =============================================================================\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import seaborn as sns\n",
    "from scipy import stats\n",
    "from IPython.display import display\n",
    "\n",
    "sns.set_theme(style=\"whitegrid\", context=\"notebook\")\n",
    "plt.rcParams[\"figure.dpi\"] = 110\n",
    "CHURN_PALETTE = {\"No\": \"#4C72B0\", \"Yes\": \"#DD8452\"}   # blue = stay, orange = churn\n",
    "\n",
    "# Encode the target as 0/1 for the correlation maths.\n",
    "df[\"Churn_binary\"] = (df[\"Churn\"] == \"Yes\").astype(int)\n",
    "OVERALL_CHURN_RATE = df[\"Churn_binary\"].mean()\n",
    "print(f\"Overall churn rate (baseline): {OVERALL_CHURN_RATE:.1%}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "NUMERIC_FEATURES = [\"tenure\", \"MonthlyCharges\", \"TotalCharges\"]\n",
    "CATEGORICAL_FEATURES = [\n",
    "    \"gender\", \"SeniorCitizen\", \"Partner\", \"Dependents\", \"PhoneService\",\n",
    "    \"MultipleLines\", \"InternetService\", \"OnlineSecurity\", \"OnlineBackup\",\n",
    "    \"DeviceProtection\", \"TechSupport\", \"StreamingTV\", \"StreamingMovies\",\n",
    "    \"Contract\", \"PaperlessBilling\", \"PaymentMethod\",\n",
    "]\n",
    "\n",
    "def cramers_v(x: pd.Series, y: pd.Series) -> float:\n",
    "    \"\"\"Bias-corrected Cramer's V (0..1) association between two categoricals.\"\"\"\n",
    "    confusion = pd.crosstab(x, y)\n",
    "    chi2 = stats.chi2_contingency(confusion, correction=False)[0]\n",
    "    n = confusion.to_numpy().sum()\n",
    "    phi2 = chi2 / n\n",
    "    r, k = confusion.shape\n",
    "    phi2corr = max(0.0, phi2 - ((k - 1) * (r - 1)) / (n - 1))\n",
    "    rcorr = r - ((r - 1) ** 2) / (n - 1)\n",
    "    kcorr = k - ((k - 1) ** 2) / (n - 1)\n",
    "    denom = min((kcorr - 1), (rcorr - 1))\n",
    "    return np.sqrt(phi2corr / denom) if denom > 0 else np.nan\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"{len(NUMERIC_FEATURES)} numeric + {len(CATEGORICAL_FEATURES)} categorical features ready.\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2cd62115",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 5.2 Numeric features vs Churn\n",
    "\n",
    "We have three number columns — `tenure`, `MonthlyCharges`, `TotalCharges` — and we want to know: *does this number look different for customers who left vs customers who stayed?*\n",
    "\n",
    "**5.2a — the overlapping histograms**\n",
    "\n",
    "Draw two curves on the same chart: one for churned customers (orange), one for stayed customers (blue).\n",
    "- Curves sitting on top of each other → the feature can't tell the two groups apart → weak predictor.\n",
    "- Curves shifted apart → churners and stayers have different values → useful predictor.\n",
    "- The `tenure` chart also shows churners bunched up in the first few months, then thinning out — that uneven shape is why we'll later create a `tenure_bin` bucket feature.\n",
    "\n",
    "**5.2b — the score table**\n",
    "\n",
    "Instead of eyeballing charts, give each feature a single number called **point-biserial r**:\n",
    "- Close to 0 → the number barely differs between the two groups → weak signal.\n",
    "- Close to +1 or −1 → the number differs a lot → strong signal.\n",
    "- Negative sign → *more* of this feature = *less* churn (e.g. long-tenure customers rarely leave).\n",
    "- Positive sign → *more* of this feature = *more* churn (e.g. high monthly charges).\n",
    "\n",
    "The table is sorted by `abs_r` (the size of the score, ignoring direction) so the most useful feature is always at the top.\n",
    "\n",
    "> **What to expect:** `tenure` should score strongly negative, `MonthlyCharges` positive, `TotalCharges` negative. If the signs are flipped, something is wrong."
   ]
  },
