   "source": [
    "### 5.7 Key takeaways\n",
    "\n",
    "**What drives churn (strongest predictors):**\n",
    "- **`tenure` (low)** — new customers are far more likely to leave. The single strongest signal (r ~ −0.42).\n",
    "- **Month-to-month `Contract` & electronic-check `PaymentMethod`** — no long-term commitment makes it easy to walk away (Cramer's V ~ 0.47 each).\n",
    "- **Fiber optic `InternetService`**, no **`OnlineSecurity`** / **`TechSupport`** — customers getting less value from the service churn more.\n",
    "- **Higher `MonthlyCharges`** — more expensive bill nudges churn up (r ~ +0.27).\n",
    "\n",
    "**What doesn't matter (drop these):**\n",
    "- `gender` (V ~ 0.007) and `PhoneService` (V ~ 0.035) carry almost no churn signal. With 594k rows even a trivial difference looks \"statistically significant\" — always rank by effect size, not p-value.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Redundant features → engineer new ones:**\n",
    "- `tenure` and `TotalCharges` say the same thing (stay longer → pay more total), so we'll create `ChargesPerMonth` (rate, not total).\n",
    "- The six internet add-ons all show \"No internet service\" together → collapse into one `HasInternet` yes/no flag.\n",
    "- Churn spikes in the first few months then levels off → bucket `tenure` into ranges (`tenure_bin`) instead of using it as a raw number."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "70d375a2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": "### 5.8 Modelling decisions from bivariate analysis\n\nWhat the findings change in the pipeline (Member 1) and model choice:\n\n**Engineer 3 features**\n- `ChargesPerMonth = TotalCharges / tenure` - breaks the `tenure`<->`TotalCharges` collinearity (5.5); separates spend *rate* from *duration*.\n- `HasInternet` - collapses the six add-ons locked to `InternetService` (5.6) into one flag, cutting redundant columns.\n- `tenure_bin` - captures the non-linear early-tenure churn spike (5.2) that a linear `tenure` term misses.\n\n**Feature selection**\n- Drop / deprioritise `gender` (V ~ 0.007) and `PhoneService` (V ~ 0.035) - no churn signal; harmless to trees but noise for the linear baseline.\n\n**Encoding (by type)**\n- Numeric (`tenure`, `MonthlyCharges`, `TotalCharges`): `RobustScaler` - histograms show skew/outliers.\n- Binary categoricals -> `OrdinalEncoder`; multi-level (`Contract`, `PaymentMethod`, `InternetService`) -> `OneHotEncoder`.\n\n**Imbalance & metric**\n- 22.5% churn -> `SMOTE` inside CV folds only; judge models on ROC-AUC / F1, not accuracy.\n\n**Model family**\n- Signal is part linear (`tenure`, `MonthlyCharges`) and part non-linear/categorical (`Contract`, `PaymentMethod`, the tenure spike) -> tree ensembles should beat the linear baseline; expect the champion to be a tree model."
  }
